---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Co-selling is a coordination problem, not a relationship problem — JWM" activePage="writing">

  <article class="post">

    <header class="post-header">
      <div class="post-header__meta">
        <span class="post-topic">Business strategy</span>
        <span class="post-dot"></span>
        <span class="post-length">6 min read</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="post-title">Co-selling is a coordination problem, not a relationship problem</h1>
      <p class="post-subtitle">Most co-sell advice focuses on building strong partner relationships. That matters. But the deals that stall don't stall because the relationship is bad — they stall because two teams showed up to a merchant call with different answers.</p>
    </header>

    <div class="post-body">

      <div class="post-content">

        <section class="post-section">
          <h2>Why vendor misalignment in front of a merchant is so expensive</h2>
          <p>I've been in co-sell situations with Shopify where the pre-call alignment was tight, and ones where it wasn't. The difference in how those calls land is not subtle.</p>
          <p>When two vendors walk into a merchant call with different answers to the same question — even slightly different answers — the merchant doesn't see a nuanced technical discussion. They see uncertainty. They start wondering which answer to trust, whether the two teams have actually worked together before, and whether the complexity they're sensing in the room will follow them into implementation. Deals that should close in that meeting get pushed. Timelines slip. Stakeholders who weren't in the room get looped in to "get a second opinion."</p>
          <p>The cost of misalignment compounds fast. A single inconsistent answer on a payment gateway recommendation — something as specific as whether Phase 1 should be Braintree or Shopify Payments — can turn a confident merchant into a hesitant one. And once a merchant is hesitant, the sales cycle extends in ways that are difficult to recover from cleanly.</p>
          <p>I've watched it happen. I've also watched what happens when you get it right. The merchant doesn't notice the coordination — they just experience the call as unusually smooth. They leave with clarity. That's the standard worth building toward.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="post-section">
          <h2>The pre-call alignment habit that changes everything</h2>
          <p>The single highest-leverage habit I've built in co-sell work is simple: never walk into a merchant-facing meeting without a dedicated sync with your partner team first. Not a quick Slack message. A real conversation where you work through the hard question together before the merchant is in the room.</p>
          <p>On the PRN Vision engagement — a two-brand healthcare migration co-sold with Shopify Professional Services — the payment gateway question was the defining technical constraint of the deal. Cybersource couldn't be directly imported by Shopify. There were multiple possible paths forward, and reasonable people on both sides had different initial instincts about which one to recommend.</p>
          <p>We resolved it before we ever sat down with the merchant. A dedicated Shopify-Recharge alignment call, focused entirely on the gateway question, where we stress-tested the options against each other and arrived at a unified recommendation. By the time we were in front of PRN, there was one answer. One rationale. No hedging, no "well, from Shopify's perspective..." and "from Recharge's perspective..." Just: here's what we recommend, here's why, here's the phasing.</p>
          <p>That preparation is invisible to the merchant. It should be. They're not paying to watch two vendors coordinate in real time — they're paying for the output of that coordination delivered cleanly and with confidence.</p>
        </section>

        <div class="pull-quote">
          "Merchants don't want to watch two vendors figure it out. They want to know what you've already figured out together."
        </div>

        <section class="post-section">
          <h2>How to handle genuine disagreements between partner teams</h2>
          <p>Pre-call alignment doesn't always produce instant consensus. Sometimes there's a genuine disagreement — a technical judgment call where Shopify's SE and Recharge's SE have different instincts, or a commercial question where the two teams have different incentives.</p>
          <p>The rule I've landed on: resolve it before the call, or make a deliberate decision together about how to present it. What you can't do is let it surface live as an unresolved debate in front of a merchant who is trying to make a decision.</p>
          <p>When the disagreement is technical — which path is more reliable, which sequencing reduces risk — the right move is to push until you reach a shared view. This usually means one person has to update their position based on new information from the other. That's a good outcome. The partner team often has context you don't, and vice versa. The pre-call sync is where that information exchange actually happens.</p>
          <p>When the disagreement is more fundamental — a genuine difference in what each vendor thinks is best for the merchant — the honest move is to flag it explicitly to your counterpart and agree on how to frame it. "We have two options here and there are tradeoffs to each" is a legitimate merchant-facing position. It just needs to be a coordinated one, not a surprise.</p>
          <p>What doesn't work is one vendor undermining the other's position in front of a merchant, even implicitly. "That's one way to look at it" followed by a different recommendation is a trust-eroding move that the merchant will notice even if they don't say so.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="post-section">
          <h2>What "one voice" actually looks like in a multi-vendor deal</h2>
          <p>One voice doesn't mean one person does all the talking. It means the two vendors are oriented around the same goal — the merchant's success — and have done enough coordination upstream that they're complementing each other rather than competing for authority in the room.</p>
          <p>In practice, this means deciding in advance who owns which parts of the conversation. On a typical Shopify-Recharge co-sell, there's a natural division: Shopify owns the commerce platform conversation, Recharge owns the subscription layer. The integration points are where you need to be explicit about handoffs — who answers the question about how Recharge interacts with Shopify's checkout, for example, matters more than who answers a question that clearly belongs to one platform or the other.</p>
          <p>It also means listening actively when your partner is talking, not preparing your next point. Some of the most damaging moments in co-sell calls happen when one vendor steps on the other's answer because they stopped listening at the point they thought they knew where it was going. The merchant notices. It signals internal misalignment even when there isn't any.</p>
          <p>The mechanics are learnable. Pre-call sync, clear ownership of conversation threads, active listening, a shared commitment to a single recommendation. None of it is complicated. What it requires is treating the coordination work as part of the job — not as overhead before the real work starts. The call is the output. The coordination is the work.</p>
        </section>

      </div>

      <aside class="post-sidebar">
        <div class="sidebar-block">
          <p class="sidebar-label">About this post</p>
          <p class="sidebar-text">Drawn from direct co-sell experience with Shopify Professional Services across multiple enterprise deals — including PRN Vision and FASTer Way to Fat Loss.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sidebar-block">
          <p class="sidebar-label">Filed under</p>
          <p class="sidebar-tag">Business strategy</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sidebar-block">
          <p class="sidebar-label">Read time</p>
          <p class="sidebar-text">6 min</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sidebar-block">
          <p class="sidebar-label">Related reading</p>
          <a href={`${base}writing/se-role`} class="sidebar-link">The SE role nobody describes accurately in a job posting →</a>
          <a href={`${base}writing/churn-product-problem`} class="sidebar-link">Churn is a product problem wearing a retention costume →</a>
        </div>
      </aside>

    </div>

  </article>

  <div class="post-footer">
    <a href={`${base}writing`} class="post-footer__back">← All writing</a>
    <a href="mailto:jmuhlenberg16@yahoo.com" class="post-footer__cta">Get notified when new posts go up →</a>
  </div>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .post { position: relative; z-index: 1; }

  .post-header {
    padding: 9rem 3rem 4rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    max-width: 720px;
  }
  .post-header__meta {
    display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }
  .post-topic { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.62rem; letter-spacing: 0.16em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--accent); }
  .post-length { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.62rem; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text-muted); }
  .post-dot { width: 3px; height: 3px; border-radius: 50%; background: var(--border-mid); }

  .post-title {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 3.5vw, 3rem);
    line-height: 1.1;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .post-subtitle {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    font-weight: 300;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  .post-body {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 260px;
    gap: 5rem;
    padding: 4rem 3rem;
    align-items: start;
  }

  .post-content { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 2.5rem; max-width: 640px; }

  .post-section { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1rem; }
  .post-section h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.35rem;
    line-height: 1.2;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
  }
  .post-section p {
    font-size: 0.97rem;
    line-height: 1.85;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }
  .post-section p em { font-style: italic; color: var(--text-primary); }

  .pull-quote {
    border-left: 2px solid var(--accent);
    padding: 0.5rem 0 0.5rem 1.5rem;
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    font-style: italic;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    margin: 0.5rem 0;
  }

  .post-sidebar {
    position: sticky;
    top: 7rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .sidebar-block {
    padding: 1.25rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.5rem;
  }
  .sidebar-block:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .sidebar-label { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.58rem; letter-spacing: 0.14em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text-muted); }
  .sidebar-text { font-size: 0.8rem; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--text-secondary); }
  .sidebar-tag { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.62rem; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--accent); }
  .sidebar-link { font-size: 0.78rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--text-secondary); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .sidebar-link:hover { color: var(--accent); }

  .post-footer {
    position: relative; z-index: 1;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    padding: 2rem 3rem;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
  }
  .post-footer__back,
  .post-footer__cta {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.68rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    transition: color 0.2s;
  }
  .post-footer__back:hover,
  .post-footer__cta:hover { color: var(--accent); }
</style>